Section 3.1 (Edition 8, pg 213-216) 5, 31

Since the list is sorted in a nondecreasing order we can do as follows:

  1. Create an empty output list to contain duplicates.
  2. Compare the two first elements of the input list.
    • If they are of the same value and not already in the output list, then add the value to the output list.
    • Otherwise, go to 1. and consider the next two elements in the input list.
  3. When at the end of the list, return the output list.

Here is an example using Python:

def find_duplicates(list):
    n = len(list)
    duplicates = []
    for i in range(0, n-1):
        if list[i] == list[i+1] and list[i] not in duplicates:
            duplicates.append(list[i])
    return duplicates

def find_duplicates(list):
    n = len(list)
    duplicates = []
    for i in range(0, n-1):
        if list[i] == list[i+1] and list[i] not in duplicates:
            duplicates.append(list[i])
    return duplicates

We can assume that the strings are of equal length (otherwise they cannot be anagrams).

a) Two strings are anagrams of eachother if and only if they have the same number of each letter.

Python example (using the built-in counting function):

def is_anagram(s1, s2):
    for c in s1:
        if s1.count(c) != s2.count(c):
            return False
    return True
def is_anagram(s1, s2):
    for c in s1:
        if s1.count(c) != s2.count(c):
            return False
    return True

If you don't want to use the built-in couting function s.count(c), you could of course make your own function counting the number of times a character c appears in the string s. For example:

def count(s, c):
    n = 0
    for k in s:
        if k == c:
            n = n + 1
    return n
def count(s, c):
    n = 0
    for k in s:
        if k == c:
            n = n + 1
    return n

b) If we sort the letters in each strings they should become the same if and only if the strings are anagrams of eachother.

Python example (using the built-in sorting function):

def is_anagram(s1, s2):
    return sorted(s1) == sorted(s2)
def is_anagram(s1, s2):
    return sorted(s1) == sorted(s2)

This returns the truth value of sorted(s1) == sorted(s2) which is, as noted above, the truth value of the statement "s1 and s2 are anagrams of eachother".

Of course, you could implement any sorting algorithm of your choice instead of using the built-in sorted function.

Example usage:

>>> is_anagram("santa", "satan")
True
>>> is_anagram("santa", "satan")
True

Big-O notation
Recall that we write f(x)=\mathcal{O}(g(x))f(x)=O(g(x))f(x)=\mathcal{O}(g(x))f(x)=O(g(x)) if (and only if) there exists some positive real number MMMM and a real number x_0x0x_0x0​ such that |f(x)|\leq Mg(x)∣f(x)∣≤Mg(x)|f(x)|\leq Mg(x)∣f(x)∣≤Mg(x) for all x\geq x_0x≥x0x\geq x_0x≥x0​.

From some point and onwards, M g(x)Mg(x)M g(x)Mg(x) will be larger than f(x)f(x)f(x)f(x). We're saying something about how the value of ffff grows as the input increases.

Example
For example, consider the polynomial f(x) = 3x^3+2x^2+xf(x)=3x3+2x2+xf(x) = 3x^3+2x^2+xf(x)=3x3+2x2+x. Since we're interested in describing the behaviour of ffff when xxxx gets big, let us assume that x>1x>1x>1x>1. In that case, x^2<x^3x2<x3x^2<x^3x2<x3 and x<x^3x<x3x<x^3x<x3 so we see that

f(x) = 3x^3+2x^2+x < 3x^3+2x^3+x^3 = 6 x^3.
f(x)=3x3+2x2+x<3x3+2x3+x3=6x3.f(x) = 3x^3+2x^2+x < 3x^3+2x^3+x^3 = 6 x^3. f(x)=3x3+2x2+x<3x3+2x3+x3=6x3.

So we have |f(x)| \leq M g(x)∣f(x)∣≤Mg(x)|f(x)| \leq M g(x)∣f(x)∣≤Mg(x) where M=6M=6M=6M=6 and g(x)=x^3g(x)=x3g(x)=x^3g(x)=x3, and hence f(x)=\mathcal{O}(x^3)f(x)=O(x3)f(x)=\mathcal{O}(x^3)f(x)=O(x3). Note that the absolute value |\cdot|∣⋅∣|\cdot|∣⋅∣ didn't matter in this case as f(x)f(x)f(x)f(x) is always positive (for x>1x>1x>1x>1).

a) For the polynomial p(x) = 3x^2+x+1p(x)=3x2+x+1p(x) = 3x^2+x+1p(x)=3x2+x+1, we have n=2n=2n=2n=2, a_2=3a2=3a_2=3a2​=3, a_1=1a1=1a_1=1a1​=1, a_0=1a0=1a_0=1a0​=1. We want to evaluate this polynomial in c=2c=2c=2c=2 using Horner's method.

Initial step y := a_2 = 3y:=a2=3y := a_2 = 3y:=a2​=3
For loop (i=1i=1i=1i=1) y := y\cdot c+ a_1 = 3\cdot 2 + 1 = 7y:=y⋅c+a1=3⋅2+1=7y := y\cdot c+ a_1 = 3\cdot 2 + 1 = 7y:=y⋅c+a1​=3⋅2+1=7
For loop (i=2i=2i=2i=2) y := y\cdot c+ a_0 = 7\cdot 2 + 1 = 15y:=y⋅c+a0=7⋅2+1=15y := y\cdot c+ a_0 = 7\cdot 2 + 1 = 15y:=y⋅c+a0​=7⋅2+1=15

In total we did two multiplications and two additions to evaluate the polynomial.
